column1: On 27 February 2023, will the combined number of likes and retweets of the most recent @theRCN tweet as of 14 February 2023 (UK time) that contains the hashtag #FairPayforNursing exceed 4,000?
column6: ['Health', 'Non-US Politics']
When I revised my forecast last time I was misled by the new views count on Twitter (19K) and confused it for the number of likes, which is still only 285 with 94 retweets.
Last correction downwards as nothing changed since my last prediction.
Government negotiations, strike on pause
All of the tweets from Feb 14th that use the #FairPayforNursing have less then 200 likes and retweets currently.

The most recent tweet as of 14 February 2023 turned out to be nothing special and therefore will most likely go unnoticed by the majority of users who are not always following what @theRCN is tweeting.

Done with @aiken, Looking at previous tweets looks very unlikely that the tweet will gain over 4k likes and retweets, only 1/20 have done so in the past. It is not on a strike day so not likely that will have high buzz.
Things seem to change, "share this post if you agree" may turn out a powerful slogan and it may suffice if only a fraction of all NHS staff active on twitter follows the advice.

Depends upon how the hashtag is used, who the protestors target with their pleas and how much damage the upcoming strikes and planned marches inflict on public perception. Who's to blame for the shortcomings of the NHS? So far... not one person, but a cold, uncaring system?

They post every couple of hours during the day and mostly get under 100 likes and retweets. It takes times to build up that much engagement on a tweet. So chances are even if the latest tweet at midnight on 27 Feb is an absolute banger, it won't have had time to get to 4k likes/RTs.
How many engagements (likes + rt’s) does @theRCN usually gets?

Will update based on the reactions to the Jan 17th and 18th strike and on Feb 6th and 7th strike. If my understanding is correct, assuming there are 5 tweets on say 13th Feb 2023 then the last tweet is the one that will be considered assuming all those tweets have the hashtag mentioned in the question.
They never seem to get very close to that mark at all.

Don’t have the impression, in my experience, that tweets, especially like these(no jokes, memes,… but “now”-news), still “build up” a lot after 2-3 days… ? Deff. not exponantially…

I applied the same resolution criteria for tweets up to 2 weeks ago in the month leading up to 2 weeks ago. About [omitted] of the tweets fit the criteria. But there were lots of repeat tweets and low-performing quote tweets that don't seem to be occurring as much now, so the chances may be higher. Then you have the potential for increased awareness of the issue due to the strikes in January 2023. And you also have a growing followership.
